<DOCNO> AP900924-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
champions of a source of clean and abundant 
energy blew into town today arguing that america could live 
contentedly without any countrys oil if it only would harness the 
wind 
the american wind energy association brought together 300 
engineers consultants manufacturers scientists and visionaries 
to discuss the possibilities of using wind power to produce a 
substantial percentage of the nations electricity 
today the wind generates only a trifling fraction of the 
nations power 
more than 15000 wind turbines are in commercial use in 
california the worlds pioneer in windgenerated electricity 
they produce 22 billion kilowatts a year thats the equivalent 
of 35 million barrels of oil somewhat less than half of one days 
imports 
its also about 1 percent of the electricity the state consumes 
or an amount equal to the power used in all the homes of san 
francisco 
wind its advocates say is domestic and abounding the turbines 
it turns emit no carbon dioxide the villain in acid rain o other 
pollutants and dont contribute to the greenhouse effect the 
warming of the atmosphere 
according to randall swisher executive director of the 
association a new study establishes the immense potential of 
wind energy to meet americas energy needs 
the study said 15 percent of the area of the 48 contiguous 
states have usable winds averaging 16 mph or more at 50 meters 
above the ground similar to the winds that turn californias 
turbines 
such winds are being costeffectively developed today using 
current technology swisher said 
he said only four states alabama mississippi florida and 
louisiana lack commercial wind potential 
the study was conducted by pacific northwest laboratories 
operated by battelle memorial institute for the energy department 
the wind association capitalizing on concerns aroused by the 
persian gulf crisis sent its supporters to capitol hill to make 
the case for wind power 
mike marvin director of government affairs said the energy 
department as a response to the iraqkuwait situation had 
considered proposing a subsidy of 2 cents per kilowatt hour for 
windgenerated electricity but the advice was not taken by the 
white house 
marvin said advocates would argue that windgenerated 
electricity should be exempt from any energy tax congress enacts 
asked if there are any downsides to tapping the winds marvin 
said some people object to the eerie sight of miles and miles of 
slowly turning turbines and some object to the noise they make but 
technological advances have made the turbines hardly more noisy 
than the wind itself he said 
i happen to think its beautiful to see the rows and rows of 
wind turbines he said 
in addition to the areas with sustained winds averaging 16 mph 
or more pacific northwest laboratories found that 14 percent of 
the land area of the united states has winds averaging 14 mph or 
more 
swisher said the next generation of wind turbines will make 
development of those slower winds costeffective by the late 1990s 
when that happens he said america will be capable of producing 
more electricity than it uses by relying solely on the wind 
the report said california has developed only onefifth of its 
areas with 16 mph wind potential 
moreover it said californias wind potential is exceeded in 13 
states north dakota texas kansas montana south dakota 
nebraska wyoming oklahoma minnesota iowa colorado new mexico 
and idaho three states new york illinois and michigan have a 
potential equal to californias 
so far renewable energy sources geothermal solar and wind 
power account for only a tiny fraction of the nations energy 
supply onequarter of one quadrillion btus of energy in 1987 the 
country consumed 76 quadrillion in 1987 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

