<TEXT>
after months of bitter debate the board of 
supervisors recommended monday that the earthquakeruined 
embarcadero freeway be torn down and replaced by a groundlevel or 
underground road 
many longtime residents saw the earthquake damage as an 
opportunity to get rid of the elevated freeway which blocks views 
of san francisco bay and covers some prime real estate 
but merchants have demanded speedy repairs for the road which 
serves chinatown and the north beach restaurant district 
the resolution approved by the supervisors is strictly advisory 
because the state and federal transportation departments have final 
say on what to do about the 15mile stretch of freeway 
interstate 480 that has been shut since the oct 17 earthquake 
that damaged much of the city 
i congratulate the board an exultant mayor art agnos told a 
hastily called news conference he said he hoped there is enough 
state and federal money available to replace the embarcadero 
freeway with a surface or subsurface artery it connects chinatown 
and north beach with the bay bridge which leads to oakland 
chinatown merchants occasionally hooted at supervisors speeches 
that favored tearing down the freeway 
the mayor said he didnt want the elevated freeway to be knocked 
down until it is known there will be enough money to build a 
replacement partly on the surface and partly underground the 
resolution passed monday says virtually the same thing 
the cost for the road agnos favors is estimated at 135 million 
the mayor labeled the freeway a terrible blight on the face of 
our city for the last 35 years 
the boards 65 vote which came after 4 hours of speechmaking 
was characterized as a signal to the california department of 
transportation and the federal government that san francisco has 
finally made up its civic mind 
the board has been accused of repeatedly delaying the decision 
for political reasons 
</TEXT>
