<TEXT>
a group of leading environmental organizations 
is trying to break into one of americas richest sources of funding 
the annual workplace charity campaigns widely identified with the 
united way 
the 23member environmental federation of america has 
participated in federal state and city government employee charity 
campaigns in the two years since its founding 
now it is trying to get its foot in the door of corporate 
payroll deduction campaigns as well 
kal stein the federations executive director said he hopes to 
be raising 400 million a year for environmental causes within 10 
years this years goal is a more modest 7 million 
we dont want to hurt united way we want to complement what 
they do stein told reporters recently 
stein said research showed that when employees are given more 
options in a workplace charity drive they increase their giving 
with united way getting as much as before 
in fact united way charities generally did better than their 
average when faced with multiple choice campaigns says a 
statement prepared by the federation 
that is not our experience responded tony de cristofaro 
spokesman for united way of america in alexandria va when there 
are multiple groups competing there are fewer dollars for local 
health and human needs 
de cristofaro said the 1400 local united way campaigns make 
their own decisions about what groups qualify to share in workplace 
donations 
in some places environmental causes are included in other 
places they are not he said in an interview clearly people in 
the local community know best whats needed 
local leaders of many united way campaigns have been taking a 
new look at what sorts of charities should be included de 
cristofaro said 
united ways need to examine what theyre doing in the light of 
what donors want to do he said what the communities have been 
counting on us to do is deal with the priority health and human 
services needs in the communities 
stein said his new national organization was affiliated with 
similar environmental federations set up in recent years in 
california oregon and washington to participate in workplace 
charity campaigns 
one of the environmental federation of americas first campaigns 
among workers at a private business will be carried out this year 
at the washington law firm arnold and porter which has about 1000 
employees 
james w jones the firms managing partner said the decision 
to participate was intended to give employees a wider range of 
choices and to help identify arnold and porter with environmental 
protection 
environmental concerns if not the issue of the 1990s is 
going to be one of the issues of the 1990s he said 
the 23 groups that make up the federation include the wilderness 
society friends of the earth the environmental defense fund the 
natural resources defense council the national audubon society and 
the sierra club legal defense fund 
donations can be designated for a particular group of the money 
that is not earmarked half is divided equally among the 23 
federation members and the rest is split up in proportion to how 
often each group was designated by other donors 
stein said the federations administration costs were about 8 
percent of total donations 
participating groups are required to meet standards on financial 
accounting and on policy stein said for example groups 
advocating illegal direct action are not accepted 
treespikers need not apply he said 
the federation expects to add a limited number of new groups 
each year and is not sure how it will respond to expected 
applications from organizations with an environmental connection 
but a primary focus on animal rights peace energy or some other 
topic 
this is a tough question deciding what is an environmental 
group stein said that will evolve on a casebycase basis 
