charlestons historic four corners of 
law is only threequarters occupied these days 
charleston countys 198yearold courthouse which is on one of 
those corners stands empty its windows still taped to protect 
them from hurricane hugo one year ago 
it might appear that the building on the foundation of south 
carolinas first statehouse has been forgotten since the stomms 
135 mph winds ripped off the roof 
looks are deceiving 
plans are under way to renovate the historic courthouse at 
meeting and broad streets charlestons most famous intersection 
buildings at the intersections four corners st michaels 
episcopal church city hall the federal courthouse and the county 
courthouse represent gods law as well as city federal and state 
law 
some historians say james hoban the charleston architect who 
designed the first white house drew heavily on the courthouse in 
his design the original white house was burned by the british in 
the war of 1812 
before hugo architect dinos liollio was hired to study 
renovation of the courthouses exterior after hugo the work was 
expanded to include interior renovations replacing the roof and 
reinforcing the building to withstand earthquakes 
the county in the meantime moved its courts to north 
charleston 
renovations may cost about 55 million and take more than a 
year when plans are complete but the exterior should remain much 
as it is 
as for the interior we dont know at this time the building 
has to respond to the needs of the 21st century although it was 
built in the 18th century liollio said 
