<TEXT>
critics say salman rushdies first book since 
irans call for his death a lighthearted fairy tale for children 
also carries a serious message for adults 
reviewers marveled sunday that rushdie could write with such 
mischievous humor despite 19 months in hiding under police guard 
during that time he has moved constantly and been separated from 
his wife the american novelist marianne wiggins 
most critics however also see signs of pain and desperation in 
the prose of haroun and the sea of stories 
the late ayatollah ruhollah khomeini called for rushdies death 
after the authors novel the satanic verses was deemed 
blasphemous to islam 
the new book tells the tale of a hindu storyteller whose talent 
is suddenly destroyed by a fanatical dictator who poisons the 
springs of his inspiration the storytellers brave son haroun 
eventually defeats the enemy of stories and restores his fathers 
gift 
rushdie dedicates the book to his own son with these lines 
as i wander far from view 
read and bring me home to you 
british writer anthony burgess reviewing the book in the 
observer newspaper said the dedication renews rage at the 
stupidity of the islamic deathmongers burning a book they do not 
have the intelligence to understand 
burgess called it a great tribute to the resilience of mr 
rushdies beleaguered spirit that he should write so charmingly 
funny a book 
it is a book to enjoy and not to explicate but if we wish we 
can take it as a piece of swiftian outrage at human folly disguised 
as a childrens tale burgess wrote 
rushdie a british citizen born into a moslem family in india 
was sentenced to death feb 14 1989 even after khomeinis death 
last year the sentence was not lifted by iranian leaders 
rushdie has since published poetry and several essays and 
reviews but haroun and the sea of stories is his first book 
since he went into hiding 
it will be published by granta books in britain on sept 27 and 
in the united states next year 
graham lord literary editor of the sunday express said rushdie 
has managed during his awful captivity to write a remarkably 
lighthearted almost mischievous childrens book 
but lord found poignant autobiographical shadows of rushdies 
own dreadful predicament especially in the remark of one 
character who said happy endings are much rarer in stories and 
also in life than most people think 
coming from rushdie in apparently unending captivity that 
sounds like a desperate cry echoing in the dark lord said 
david hughes in the mail on sunday said salman rushdie the 
flags of merriment flying throughout his allegory wins a grim 
fight of his own his fine book written in conditions in which 
such ebullience of mood takes courage is a great reechoing cry 
for freedom of word and view for the inarguable truth in a good 
story 
writer and critic marina warner reviewing the book in the 
sunday times which published several excerpts said rushdies 
jauntiness under sentence of death is matter for wonder 
enough but what is even more so is the absolutely unpompous 
treatment of the villains in the story 
