<TEXT>
federal health officials are collaborating 
with several hundred physicians in the united states and canada to 
gather more information about the progression of the infection that 
leads to aids 
the study will give medical researchers a better picture of 
which symptoms and diseases are most common in different groups of 
patients infected with the human immunodeficiency virus or hiv 
which causes aids officials said in announcing the study monday 
it also will provide information on what treatments patients are 
using and will help researchers identify medical changes that occur 
as hiv infection progresses towards acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome 
health and human services secretary louis sullivan said the 
study was expected to result in the most comprehensive collection 
of information on hivinfected persons amassed in the history of 
the aids epidemic 
patient confidentiality will be protected he added 
the more information we have about hivinfected persons the 
faster we can advance our aids research said hhs assistant 
secretary for health james mason 
the study will allow researchers to compile a data base on a 
broad spectrum of hiv patients and will help physicians identify 
patients who can participate in clinical trials of experimental 
drugs officials said 
more than 30 communitybased clinics and programs in the united 
states and canada will participate in the study they include 18 
sponsored by the national institute of allergy and infectious 
diseases and 15 sponsored by the american foundation for aids 
research 
several hundred physicians will be able to enroll patients they 
see at these clinics and programs as well as patients they see in 
their private practices these physicians care for more than 60000 
hivinfected patients according to the research foundation 
every three to six months during a regular clinic visit 
physicians will ask all patients in the study a set of questions 
about their health and the drugs they are taking 
