<TEXT>
the justice department filed an unusual 
reverse discrimination lawsuit monday accusing the maryland 
lottery of bias against white men in 1983 when it set aside several 
top positions for women and minorities 
the civil rights suit alleged that maryland and its lottery 
agency violated title vii of the 1964 civil rights act by refusing 
to hire qualified white males for the four positions set aside for 
minorities in 1983 
the lawsuit was denounced by a state official as an unwarranted 
attack on a onetime effort by maryland to recruit more minorities 
into the lottery agency 
two black men a black woman and a white women were recruited 
in response to a maryland human relations commission 
investigation and determination that the lottery agency was not 
doing enough to meet affirmative action requirements said dennis 
sweeney deputy state attorney general 
the lawsuit states that the states governor then harry r 
hughes directed the lottery agency to set aside four seniorlevel 
positions for women or members of a racial minority 
the hiring policy was investigated by the us equal employment 
opportunity commission which referred complaints of discrimination 
to the justice department according to the complaint filed in 
federal court in baltimore 
ten white men complained to the eeoc in 1985 said justice 
department spokeswoman amy casner the eeoc referred the case to 
the justice department in 1988 she said 
the lottery agency which employs 108 people has 12 
seniorlevel positions she said 
the suit seeks an injunction barring the state of maryland from 
reserving lottery agency positions for women or members of a 
minority it also seeks compensation for white men who were the 
victims of the alleged discrimination 
sweeney said the justice department has rejected overtures to 
settle the case out of court but federal officials were insistent 
on obtaining a consent decree 
we dont see the profit in going to this archaeological dig of 
attempting to reconstruct this event in 1983 sweeney said all 
the actors are all now either dead or retired from state 
government 
we are hoping we can still talk about these issues and reason 
will prevail because quite frankly i think the federal courts 
have more important things to do he said 
justice department officials have sought back pay of less than 
15000 for two men who were not hired sweeney said 
reverse discrimination lawsuits are unusual but the justice 
department has filed them in the past when it determines that 
whites have been the victims of racial bias 
</TEXT>
