<TEXT>
five of eight voter initiatives including 
one that would have allowed tax credits at parochial schools are 
ineligible for the november election a judge ruled monday 
three other statewide measures on the nov 6 general election 
ballot could be disqualified under the ruling by marion county 
circuit judge richard barber among them is a measure which if 
approved would outlaw most abortions in the state 
barber said the five initiatives do not qualify because they 
wont be accompanied by financial impact statements as required by 
state law the statements estimating each measures fiscal impact 
on the state were earlier declared invalid because they werent 
certified by deadline 
both the state and a group backing the education measure said 
they would appeal barbers decision to the state court of appeals 
which could send the case to the oregon supreme court without 
ruling 
the education measure would allow tax credits of up to 2500 a 
year each for pupils at private schools including churchsupported 
schools and for children taught at home 
that measure which drew the interest of educators across the 
country also would have allowed parents to send their children 
across district lines to any public school 
it would be a travesty and an injustice if the public werent 
allowed to vote on a measure because state officials didnt do 
their job said steve buckstein spokesman for oregonians for 
educational choice 
the other measures affected by mondays ruling would limit 
property taxes to 15 percent of value shut down the trojan 
nuclear plant about 40 miles northwest of portland until waste 
disposal requirements are met ban some nonrecyclable packaging 
and establish a program to put able welfare applicants to work 
barbers ruling strikes at the heart of the initiative 
process secretary of state barbara roberts said in announcing 
the states plan to appeal it means that a legal technicaltiy 
can take away a constitutional right she said 
about 84000 registered voters signed petitions to get the 
educational initiative on the ballot while the measure on the 
nuclear plant required about 63000 signatures 
because of printing deadlines barber said the five measures 
could stay on the ballot but that votes for or against them would 
not be counted 
barbers decision was an outgrowth of earlier marion county 
circuit court rulings that the fiscal statements were invalid 
state law specifies that the secretary of state state treasurer 
and the directors of the executive and revenue departments certify 
the fiscal impact statements 
state elections director jack graham said those officials were 
polled on the aug 8 deadline and that three of four agreed to the 
statements but the statements werent signed until after the 
deadline 
if the ruling stands on appeal three more measures lacking 
fiscal impact statements also would have to be disqualified he 
said 
those measures would outlaw most abortions require parental 
notice of abortions involving minors and change taxation of some 
public employee pensions 
if all eight are disqualified three measures would be left on 
the ballot two legislative housekeeping measures and one that 
would require seat belt use they didnt require financial impact 
statements 
