<TEXT>
a 15minute walk from the glassandneon glitz of 
tokyos ginza district is a tiny enclave of older japan that is 
fighting a losing battle for survival 
a glimpse of a bygone time can be had on the islands of 
tsukudajima and tsukishima which escaped the us bombers that 
leveled much of the rest of tokyo in world war ii 
traditional woodframe houses line alleys cluttered by potted 
plants guarding every door children play in the narrow streets 
while older folk chat with old buddies preserving the slower pace 
of life that was the norm before japans economic ascent 
the feel of old edo the name of tokyo during the feudal era 
was captured one august sunday during a traditional festival that 
binds the 300 families of tsukudajima with the past 
hundreds of spectators gathered to cheer tsukudajima fishermen 
as they heaved a gilded shrine onto a barge in sumida river as part 
of a summer festival held every three years since the mid1600s 
the barge then circled the island community to bless the 
surrounding waters accompanied by priests and the music of flute 
and drums 
feverish real estate speculation however is threatening to 
destroy these remnants of prewar tokyo 
since 1988 when a 40story deluxe apartment tower was built 
next to tsukudajima and a subway line was extended to the two 
islands skyrocketing land prices have begun to take a toll 
many residents say they have been offered as much as 200000 
for their small homes some have sold out and the two 
neighborhoods are now dotted with boardedup stores and other 
property lying unused while speculators wait for land prices to 
rise further 
shocked by such speculation urban planners have been trying to 
work out a development plan for the islands before its too late 
uzumi yoshida head of chuo ward regional improvement section 
says the city government hopes to preserve the neighborhoods 
traditional role as workingclass residential areas 
but yoshida acknowledged his authority was limited 
japan has placed very few restrictions on land ownership its 
only recently with land values going through the roof that the 
government has attempted to curb speculation he said 
toshie narusawa a 52yearold tsukishima resident doubts the 
governments sincerity 
city officers are trying to raise the buildingtoland ratio 
they told me this we want to make the tsukishima area into new 
yorks manhattan she said 
narusawa believes government officials look down on the working 
people of tsukishima and tsukudajima and are convinced that modern 
apartment buildings are preferable to the traditional tiny 
fireprone homes 
but she responds there are many people who are glad to live 
in those houses and are proud of it 
so far no citizens movement has formed to defend the two 
districts 
instead since tokyo entered the modern era it has destroyed 
its past in a constant race to import all thats new to fulfill its 
role as japans showcase to the world said paul waley urban 
historian and author of tokyo now and then 
narusawa believes the districts subdivision into small 
individual plots and stubborn resistence of some longtime residents 
will thwart efforts to turn the islands into highrise jungles 
but even if the neighborhoods change locals say the festival 
will continue to provide the glue to hold the community together 
every three years former residents as well as family members 
return from all parts of japan to take part 
the festival is even helping to weld the newr parts of town to 
old tsukudajima and tsukishima says local assemblyman and festival 
organizer yoichiro fujima 
this was the first year that people from the new apartments 
could participate in the festival so if participating one time 
leads to two times two times lead to three and it continues like 
that the newcomers will help old tsukudajima retain its culture 
</TEXT>
