<TEXT>
the boy clad in a leather toga sat on a 
cowhide in a circle of male relatives and stared hard at the 
strangers knife 
the stranger squatted over the boy made a circular incision 
with his knife and seven minutes later gibson leisamato 16 was a 
man a circumcised warrior of the samburu tribe 
unflinchingly the youngster had endured the delicate operation 
without anaesthesia not until the circumciser had finished did he 
make a sound 
now i want cows gibson shouted at the end of the ordeal a 
traditional rite of passage for men among most of this east african 
nations 40odd tribes some also circumcise females but secretly 
because of a government ban 
but medical authorities are concerned about the safety of the 
tradition especially its possible contribution to the spread of 
aids kenya has nearly 10000 diagnosed cases of the deadly 
disease 
traditionally circumcisers use the same knife on any group of 
young men at a given location and time this supposedly creates a 
lifelong bond between the initiates 
but the circumciser also uses the same cloth to wipe the 
knife says duncan mutembei a male nurse working among the 
samburu some dont wash between operations 
the crude surgery invites infections and every year several 
young men bleed to death due to a slip of a knife circumcisers 
themselves sometimes pay harshly for their mistakes 
newspapers in the capital of nairobi reported the case this year 
of a circumciser who was stoned to death by an angry mob after he 
cut more than intended from one boy the youngster lived 
joseph oliech kenyas health director has proposed testing and 
licensing of the circumcisers to ensure competence most learn 
their trade as apprentices 
for the circumciser the rite is good business relatively few 
in number they perform as many as 50 operations a day earning as 
much as some laborers make in a month fees are 5 to 7 an 
operation 
six hours after his operation and still in sharp pain gibson 
stoically rejoiced in his new status as a moran or warrior of his 
northern kenya tribe 
now i am a man he said i can have girlfriends i can get 
married 
for most tribes the circumcision right is an annual event for 
the samburu it occurs only once every 15 years but for all it is 
a time of celebration dance and song 
wamba rashid an anthropologist at the university of nairobi 
explains the significance of the event for young men 
it is a way of welcoming them into adulthood before then they 
were nobodys it is a way of telling them you are no longer a 
child you have rights and responsibilities to the community 
some of those responsibilities are long gone 
samburu morans no longer defend the tribe police do and they 
dont kill lions to prove their bravery its against the law 
but after the ritual young men can have girlfriends get 
married own property and participate in other adult activities 
whatever his tribe the initiate must face the surgery bravely 
without a flinch cry or moan or shame his family 
i was so worried my son would show fear i could not eat 
before he was circumsiced said gibsons mother najoko 
after the ritual sages instruct the initiated in the tribes 
customs sometimes for up to a month 
the mutilation is talked of most says rashid but there 
is the education and psychological changes that occur 
in urban areas boys are increasingly being circumcised in 
hospitals where health risks are greatly reduced 
but many feel hospitals are for cowards so the tradition of 
facing the knife endures 
it generates respect among individuals says samuel 
lekesion a samburu and former policeman it also guarantees 
survival if i am in trouble i can always call upon my age 
mates 
</TEXT>
