<TEXT>
it has become fashionable to blame real estate 
developers for overdoing things for building too many speculative 
projects for glutting the market with buildings when demand is 
headed down 
as a result developers are often seen today as impractical 
dreamers rather than lionized as imaginative shrewd insightful 
gutsy risktakers as they were yesterday 
yes they overdid it as they are prone to do but the bankers 
did too the developers couldnt have overbuilt without the money 
and the commercial lenders of america shoveled it at them 
if the developers went from one extreme to another the bankers 
may have done so even more abruptly after building their real 
estate portfolios they have closed them down so that good 
investments and bad alike are denied 
a report by the general accounting office shows that real estate 
portfolios held by commercial banks in 1985 made up 266 percent of 
their total loans and leases after rising every year the 
percentage reached 37 percent in 1989 
it couldnt have happened of course if the banks hadnt let it 
happen but the evidence shows clearly that they thought real 
estate as an investment was becoming relatively better than 
investing in commerce and industry 
in 1985 about 35 percent of their outstanding loans were in the 
commercialindustrial category that percentage declined every year 
through 1989 when it reached 301 percent 
the performance of real estate loans deteriorated as their 
percentage of total portfolios rose in 1988 24 percent of 
commercial bank real estate loans were noncurrent in 1989 it had 
risen to 29 percent 
in those figures lies some of the reason for what seems to be a 
growing credit crunch that at first involved only small companies 
mostly developers in the northeast but which has spread to big and 
small companies everywhere 
what had been the most desired investment now seems to be the 
least desirable for developers in certain areas to obtain bank 
money today would mean dismissal for the loan officer and 
conceivably a federal investigation 
it is not the first instance of extreme behavior by banks in 
the 1970s for example they shipped billions of dollars abroad to 
less developed nations willing to pay premium rates while 
homemortgage applications were denied 
billions of dollars of those ldc loans as they are called are 
considered nonperforming now and commercial banks have been forced 
to set aside reserves to cover what some bank analysts believe are 
inevitable writeoffs 
the irony of the current crackdown on loans provoked mainly by 
the tooeasy lending policies of a few years ago is that real 
estate developments begun in the next year might be finished when 
demand is growing again 
but neither real estate development nor banking seem to be 
gifted with the farsightedness they claim both get excited when 
commercial development is at a feverish pace and they collapse 
together when the bad results are in 
history shows that some of the costliest real estate 
developments in america are ready just as the market becomes 
glutted and just before the economy turns down 
and when the economy is down and preparing for an upturn a 
couple of years hence neither seems to have the heart or the 
foresight to invest 
</TEXT>
