editors note after decades of exclusion western scholars 
recently were allowed to travel chinas fabled silk road in search 
of archaeological treasures but it was look dont touch the 
chinese are resentful of westerners hauling off vestiges of their 
heritage 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
more than 4000 years after east met west 
in the swirling sands of chinas western deserts modern 
treasureseekers are unlocking clues to the past along the ancient 
silk road 
isolated by location and for political and military reasons 
most of the silk road for decades has been closed to foreign 
scholars 
the government has jealously guarded its riches resentful of 
western archaeologists who removed thousands of priceless documents 
and works of art from the region in the late 19th and early 20th 
century 
however a recent monthlong desert expedition sponsored by the 
united nations education scientific and cultural organization gave 
about 80 foreign and chinese scholars and journalists a rare 
opportunity to travel the silk road and to discuss ways to preserve 
its ancient heritage 
marco polo genghis khan and alexander the great followed the 
silk road 
camel caravans braved the harsh desert to bring chinas silk 
roses and paper to the west they carried colorglazing techniques 
jade and cotton north and eastward into china 
the desolate taklamakan desert was originally inhabited by 
nomads and traders who built cities and bazaars in oases clinging 
tenuously to life in the desert sand 
historians who are still unearthing cataloging and 
interpreting archaeological evidence from the region say the first 
chinese conquest of the region was in the early han dynasty about 
200 to 300 bc 
despite its desolation the silk road and the surrounding desert 
is a strategic crossroads between africa europe and asia mongols 
chinese tibetans and moslem uyghurs have fought over this 
strategic territory nestled between tibet mongolia persia india 
and china 
today the region is still rocked by periodic moslem rebellions 
an antichinese riot this spring almost led to the cancellation of 
the expedition participants said 
after several postponements the expedition began on july 20 in 
xian the easternmost end of the silk road some 150 miles from 
the great wall that traditionally marked the edge of chinese 
civilization 
after the expedition ended aug 18 in the western bazaar city of 
kashgar scholars and journalists gathered in urumqi capital of 
chinas westernmost xinjiang autonomous region to review and share 
their findings 
foreign scholars traveling with the group said chinas decision 
to go ahead with the expedition apparently was intended to 
demonstrate its willingness to continue opening up to the outside 
world despite political repression following the crushing of 
studentled democracy movements in june 1989 
i think the opening to the outside world economically has 
finally begun to enter the intellectual sphere said richard b 
stamps professor of anthropology and chinese studies at oakland 
university in rochester mich 
stamps said discussion of possible joint research projects could 
eventually lead to the lifting of a ban on foreign participation in 
chinese archaeological digs 
the expedition was very useful for the foreign scholars like 
myself who have wanted all their lives to come work in china now 
we have name cards and contact people who have long worked in 
isolation stamps said 
isenbike aricanli togan professor of inner asian history at 
washington university said i have been working on the history 
of xinjiang for over 20 years and this was the first time i could 
actually see it you can imagine how excited i was 
the exchange yielded some surprises caucasian human remains 
from tombs more than 3000 years old near hami indicated a link 
between asia and europe that may explain why some languages such 
as tibetan are indoeuropean said ahmad hasan dani director of 
the pakistan center for the study of the civilization of central 
asia 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900924-0228 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
many of the scholars identified symbols and architecture proving 
ancient cultural influences from persia and india in china 
but scholars and journalists who traveled the entire 6125 miles 
of the silk road and its byways by car truck camel and donkey 
cart said they were frustrated by limits imposed as they viewed 
longawaited murals and sculptures 
the chinese are very protective and jealous of their 
copyrights said one participant who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
he said in some cases they were charging as much as 100 for 
photos and in many other cases they refused to allow photographs or 
sketching at all many scholars were forced to rely only on their 
memories of what they saw he said 
chinese leaders of the expedition say the limits were based on 
concerns about damage to the exhibits and on time constraints 
our task was not to excavate or discover archaeological 
sites said xu pingfang director of the institute of history at 
the chinese academy of social sciences many of these things have 
never been seen by foreigners before and the museums have never 
been opened before 
stamps said the constraints also were based on an international 
tradition that maintains that the finder of an archaeological 
discovery should be the first to publish the findings 
the chinese are struggling to get the massive volume of 
artifacts found in the past decade into libraries he said 
only some have been published 
the expedition raised delicate questions about the ownership and 
preservation of ancient artifacts 
many artifacts taken from the silk roads magnificent tombs 
temples and grottoes now sit in european and western museums they 
form the basis of central asian research in the west 
a call by chinese journalist li xiguang for the return of those 
treasures to china prompted some western scholars to suggest that 
some items or at least their reproductions should be returned to 
their places of origin 
others argued however that the wealth of the silk road belongs 
to all mankind and that an international effort such as that 
initiated by the getty foundation for the buddhist grottoes at 
dunhuang is needed to prevent its destruction 
dunhuangs nearly 500 caves have been called a 1600yearold 
art gallery of buddhist culture but its thousands of magnificent 
frescoes and statues are threatened by pollution and other changes 
in the environment caused partly by thousands of visitors each 
year 
members of the expedition spoke of buddhist sculptures kept in 
unroofed earthen museums that were literally disintegrating 
because local curators lacked the funds and technology to preserve 
them 
unfortunately archaeologists in china sometimes lack the 
sophisticated controls that we maintain in the west they have the 
funds to dig but not to curate their findings said one scholar 
who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the fact that we have those pieces in france has raised some 
questions about conservation said jacques gies curator at the 
guimet museum in paris 
gies said researchers in france recently have developed ways to 
extract destructive salts that ruin crude earth sculptures without 
destroying their color or quality 
we are working very hard to transmit and to preserve the 
heritage we have inherited said christa paula a researcher at 
the university of londons school of oriental and african studies 
which also has many documents and artifacts taken from sites along 
the silk road 
</TEXT>
