editors note many alcoholics shy away from alcoholics 
anonymous because of its religious overtones and now there are 
groups that offer a psychological alternative while they are 
growing they walk a thin financial line 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
for some alcoholics who cannot abide the idea of 
praying for relief from their addiction there are alternatives 
some are spinoffs from alcoholics anonymous and some are within aa 
itself 
many members of alcoholics anonymous say they need some sort of 
spiritual awareness but bill talley an atheist and a recovering 
alcoholic is one of a growing number of former drinkers who have 
found an alternative to spiritual treatment for their illness 
in some of the more sophisticated major cities such as new york 
one aa member says the organization is aware of the religious 
problem and has sanctioned groups which look for professional help 
it also tries to accommodate such diverse groups as lesbians gays 
and the deaf all of whom require adjustments in traditional aa 
procedures 
talley was a pioneer in establishing support groups for 
alcoholics who are uncomfortable with aas spiritual path to 
sobriety 
id been to many meetings for a couple of years until i 
finally went out of there screaming talley recalls 
so talley with the help of atheist madalyn murray ohair and 
her network started his own alcoholic recovery group and called it 
aaarg american atheist addiction recovery groups 
he later changed the name of his organization to methods of 
moderation and abstinence moma because some people had trouble 
with the a atheist word he says 
talley who has a denver freelance advertising consulting 
business has used his own money to keep his organization going 
its growth has been slow but steady but talley says his business 
is dying because of the stigma of being an atheist im 
running out of money its been a struggle 
in succeeding years other groups have been organized including 
secular organization for sobriety or sos started by james 
christopher in california and rational recovery rr started by 
jack trimpey also in california 
the most recent and possibly the bestorganized is the 
international association of secular recovery organizations 
founded by stanley endick at lauderdale by the sea fla 
they have far fewer members than aa which reports several 
million worldwide but they are growing talley estimates about 
15000 or more people are tied to moma and that sos and rr are 
approaching that number talley says moma is now in 89 major 
cities every state and seven countries 
talleys argument against aa goes beyond religion 
in aa they say if you think you are an alcoholic then you 
are but maybe youre not maybe youre just a drinker 
in our groups youre encouraged not only to diagnose yourself 
sensibly based on modern psychological principles but also to see 
a professional he says see what he thinks 
but talley concedes that aa works for many even though i 
dont accept their premise that this is a progressive terminal 
disease for everyone he says i accept the premise that its 
going to be terminal for some 
talley quotes studies that show a few people can learn to 
moderate their use of alcohol 
besides iasro which is aimed at uniting the alternative groups 
endiuck also heads the steven danzinger foundation a 15bed 
inpatient program 
the foundation is supported by the mother of steven danzinger a 
36yearold addict who overdosed 2 years ago after dropping out of 
aa 
he want an atheist or agnostic endick says he was 
jewish he consistently objected to his mother about the overtly 
christian overtones his mother thought maybe if he had had an 
alternative he may have recovered 
trimpey a crisis intervention counselor who had alcohol 
problems of his own before establishing rational recovery says 
were trying to protect people from further exposure to aas 
doctrine of submissiveness and powerlessness which is very 
damaging to mental health 
trimpys group differs from other groups by encouraging the 
recovering alcoholic to leave the group eventually 
theres more to life than the constant fight to stay sober 
he says 
aa offers 12 steps to recovery from alcoholism including an 
admission that we were powerless over alcoholthat a power 
greater than ourselves could restore us to sanity 
an aa member in denver who identified himself as gary k said 
the power neednt be a theistic god 
the big book aas 575page bible says god as you 
understand him and each individual is free to find his or her own 
conception thats what separates aa from religion 
many use the group itself as the power many will seek the god 
of religion each individual is left to his or her own devices 
the alternative groups use some of the same methods but one of 
momas positions is that people can learn to use virtually all 
psychoactive substances with moderation abstinence however is 
preferred 
the alternative groups have variations of aas 12 steps one of 
momas ten criteria calls for a member to assume 
responsibility for ones own life though at times choosing to seek 
the help of others another calls on members to be objective 
rational and scientific and to apply the laws of logic and 
scientific method in daily living 
one of the 11 tenets of rational recovery states the idea 
that i need something greater than myself upon which to rely is 
only another dependency idea and dependency is my original 
problem 
aa has no opinion on alternative alcohol programs said gary 
k we try to be as inclusive as we can beas far as the 
alternative things we do not endorse anything but great if it 
works tell us about it our interest is solely recovery from 
alcoholism 
aa which is selfsupporting through contributions doesnt 
allow any one person to contribute more than 1000 a year gary k 
says 
talley doesnt have that problem 
out of all the mail ive got this week this is the only 
contribution he says holding up half a dozen postage stamps 
but im grateful for that 
he thinks eventually the alternative organizations will grow 
sufficiently to mount fundraising efforts and maybe pay a salary 
id love to have a fulltime staff cranking out literature 
handling inquiries writing articles crosspollinating with the 
other organizations he says 
