<TEXT>
timberlake wertenbakers new play our 
countrys good is taking the regional theater circuit by storm 
the drama celebrates a reallife event the first theatrical 
performance in australia that was in 1789 when a group of english 
convicts staged george farquhars early 18thcentury comedy the 
recruiting officer 
does that sound unpromising and esoteric not to the london 
critics who cheered when our countrys good premiered at the 
royal court theater in 1988 and later won the olivier award for 
play of the year and not to artistic directors on the regional 
theater circuit in the united states and in canada they have made 
it one of the mostproduced new plays of this season 
our countrys good had its american premiere last fall at 
the mark taper forum in los angeles and then in april it was done 
at the remains theater in chicago the repertory theater in st 
louis has just finished a production while hartford stage in 
connecticut has a version directed by mark lamos now running 
other productions are planned for the new american theater in 
rockford ill the oregon shakespeare festival in portland 
californias berkeley repertory theater and a contemporary theater 
in seattle in canada there will be productions in edmonton 
montreal and halifax this season 
the play has wonderful insights into the ideas of making 
theater and thats always interesting to people like me says 
lamos artistic director at hartford stage where the play is on 
view through nov 3 on a larger level its about the power of 
education how education can transform peoples lives 
our countrys good originally was inspired by the 
playmaker a novel by australian writer thomas keneally 
it would be unfair to the novel to say that the play is an 
adaptation wertenbaker said in a telephone interview from a new 
hampshire vacation retreat there are characters that dont 
appear in the novel and the plot is slightly changed 
the keneally book was brought to her in london by max 
staffordclark who runs the royal court that shrine of modern 
british drama which first gave the world such classics as john 
osbornes look back in anger 
i said i wouldnt adapt the playmaker but i would be very 
interested in doing something on the same subject the playwright 
recalled 
wertenbaker used the novel as well as the fatal shore a 
history of an australian penal colony by robert hughes as the 
takingoff points for her play she also did a lot of research at 
the british museum into the journals of the reallife main 
character an idealistic lieutenant who directed the convicts in 
the farquhar comedy 
wertenbaker and the actors who eventually were cast in the play 
at the royal court also interviewed former prisoners who were 
involved in theater 
what interested me was the notion of the redemptive power of 
theater which is in the novel and i suppose was something i 
believed in anyway the playwright said we would ask them 
about what theater had meant to them they had found a great deal 
of freedom by being involved in theater during their prison 
sentences 
our countrys good is a big play 22 characters and 22 
scenes 
i wanted to follow quite a lot of characters wertenbaker 
said and thats always difficult to construct to keep the 
characters straight and to keep their stories going throughout the 
play 
wertenbaker wrote the play under deadline pressure it already 
had been scheduled to open and run in repertory with a revival of 
the recruiting officer with the same actors appearing in both 
plays 
so we had to work very fast in rehearsals she recalled i 
was getting up at 5 oclock in the morning to rewrite and i would 
bring in a scene which they would then rehearse that morning it 
was quite something 
wertenbaker went to connecticut briefly in midseptember to 
attend rehearsals of our countrys good at hartford stage and 
to answer any questions the american actors might have about her 
play 
wertenbaker did encourage the american actors not to use strong 
18thcentury accents 
we dont really known what 18thcentury accents were like 
anyway she said the play is not written in a lot of local 
dialects im a modern playwright ive just given some rhythms to 
certain characters actors should just use their natural voices and 
accents and then push it a little bit 
wertenbaker is more guarded about her private life than she is 
about her public writing 
the playwright has described herself as an 
anglofrenchamerican who lives in north london grew up in the 
south of france and went to school in the united states 
wertenbaker had her first play produced in 1983 since 1984 she 
has been a resident writer at the royal court earning recognition 
there with a play called the grace of mary traverse she has 
also had works done by the royal shakespeare company 
right now shes laboring on a new play commissioned by the 
royal court no details were revealed but she did say her deadline 
is december 
i sit down every day she said i have a little study in 
the back of my house that looks out over a garden i have privacy 
i take very precise notes the scene whos in the scene 
what they are doing in the scene i do that in longhand then i 
write on a word processor but i dont write dialogue until the 
last minute not until everything else is sorted out in the 
scene 
</TEXT>
