<TEXT>
in an open field in the center of berlin a 
low mound of debris over adolf hitlers fuehrer bunker rises 
near traces of the berlin wall the rubble of germanys bitter 
past 
neither is a monument no bronze plaques instruct visitors how 
to think about the mingled symbols of the fascist german reich and 
the cold war division of europe 
yet the questions they pose about the future are now rising as 
the lens of history tries to keep pace with the leap to unity of 
east and west germany on oct 3 recreating a country of almost 80 
million people by far the largest in europe 
the new germany like it or not will have to prove again and 
again that it is different because in being big rich and 
powerful it will look somewhat like the bad old germany 
a halfcentury ago german militarism already carrying a long 
history of making trouble for germanys neighbors forced 
blitzkrieg on europe invasion the bombing of cities occupation 
captive people and holocaust death camps to exterminate jews all 
sprang from germany 
world war ii is useful to remember said nicholas ridley a 
few months ago in the interview that led to his resignation as 
britains trade and industry secretary 
germans today are uppity ridley said they are taking over 
europe by economic power and he thought a lot of people in europe 
agreed with him 
ridley exited the political stage and the fuss was only a ripple 
in the headlong rush to unify germany yet it served as a reminder 
of the resentment germany has earned repeatedly since bismark 
united the germans under the prussian flag in 1871 
theres ample evidence that germany is conscious of a need to 
work off the evil legacies of the past 
west germany has paid 52 billion to the state of israel and to 
survivors of the holocaust there are numerous public monuments to 
the victims of naziism and memorials at deathcamp sites 
still some germans are tired of thinking about it 
germans want to be glad they dont want to walk around 
stressed confronted from morning till evening with the burden of 
history chancellor helmut kohl told british journalist david 
marsh of the financial times 
west german author patrick sueskind wrote in the weekly der 
spiegel of his confusion on seeing kohl raise a toast auf 
deutschland to germany after negotiations in moscow 
sueskind hadnt ever heard anyone toast germany and what sprang 
to his mind was auschwitz and the war 
but thats not what the chancellor meant sueskind wrote 
he didnt have the old aggressive germany in mind but rather 
the present and future germany peaceful civilized bound up into 
europe 
will the united germany be up to the political standards of the 
emerging new world order the 61 million west germans have had 45 
years experience in democracy but the 166 million east germans 
languished since the war under a communist police state many 
collaborated most were passive few resisted they werent told 
much about the holocaust 
we had to have a crash course in democracy says tino 
schwierzina who became mayor of east berlin last spring as east 
germany held its first free elections i think weve done a good 
job 
yet east german political life has been about as chaotic as the 
east german economy since the peaceful revolution in the fall of 
1989 twelve of 22 cabinet members have quit or been fired due to 
incompetence political strife or because of alleged ties to the 
oncedreaded stasi secret police organization 
the poison in the stasis 6 million files will still haunt the 
country after unification 
how hard should the police seek out those who committed crimes 
under orders from east germanys communist bosses 
can murder prosecutions be brought against those who killed 
approximately 200 people trying to cross the east germanwest 
german border including the berlin wall in the 28 years it stood 
before last nov 9 
such issues are only a few of many facing the germans after they 
vote on whether to stay with kohls centerright government or go 
for oskar lafontaines leftist social democrats 
other big domestic issues 
rebuilding substandard industry and infrastructure in the east 
and other costs of unification may require the government and 
private sector to invest an estimated 775 billion over five years 
says elmar pieroth an economics expert from kohls party the 
christian democratic union 
social subsidies will be crucial to retain the good will of 
east germans said gerhard behrendt an undersecretary in the east 
german environment ministry like many behrendt doesnt know if he 
will have a job after unification 
it was common to have two workers in a family and you got 
only an average living standard he said if production 
decreases now and jobs disappear someone must still earn money 
but how 
the east germans may have 2 million unemployed soon as one 
enterprise after another collapses west germany is a luxuryloving 
land where incomes are more than double the 765 a month reported 
in east germanys official but dubious statistics 
west germans are cruising through east germany in their bmws 
looking to reclaim family properties confiscated decades ago by the 
communists the prospect of wealthy west germans ousting jobless 
easterners from lowrent housing highlights the trouble looming for 
the next government over the disparity between east and west german 
living standards 
money indeed will be an issue west germany is rich but can 
it afford all that reconstruction money and 95 billion to moscow 
to finance the withdrawal of 370000 soviet troops from east 
germany and 3 billion for the persian gulf crisis 
a flood of refugees is testing how different todays germany is 
from the fascist one that created a flood of refugees leaving 
germany a stream of soviet jews applying to come to germany is of 
great historical irony perhaps true to historical form the bonn 
government has temporarily halted processing of applications from 
jews citing an apparently unmanageable wave with 10000 applicants 
in kiev alone 
this year west germany expects a record 120000 asylum 
applicants and 50 percent more next year 
the refugees and guest workers from turkey and southern 
europe have changed the face of germany especially in the cities 
germany today is a cosmopolitan mixture of turks yugoslavs blacks 
and asians with their own bakeries restaurants and for the turks 
a tv channel in their language 
east germanys environment in worse shape than the wests was 
poisoned by industries that were competitive only because they 
burned cheap foul brown coal and dumped untreated wastes into 
rivers the cleanup bill will be enormous 
one of the hottest topics in berlin can be identified as 
berlin as the future european metropolis 
now a city of 3 million spacious berlin will become the german 
capital bonn was always west germanys interim capital 
berlin is where the heart of the new germany beats strongest 
where unity came in the heady rush of a popular and peaceful 
rebellion last autumn 
from an isolated capitalist island in a sea of communists 
berlin has become a symbol of hope it will be the major european 
city between paris and moscow a gateway to the eastern neighbors 
who were inspired to push aside communist governments after the 
east germans showed that their regime was a paper tiger 
