<TEXT>
some of the east germans who helped open the 
door to german unity are reluctant to step inside 
dissident professor peter boethig fled the country just a few 
months before its remarkable transformation to a free nation now 
that hes back hes not sure he belongs 
katje havemann endured house arrest for more than two years and 
fought a lonely fight for change long before huge crowds joined her 
on the streets now that the communists have been overthrown 
havemann presses on with protests against the new government 
carl ordnung works for that government which won east germanys 
first free elections by promising fast capitalism and quick unity 
but ordnung now worries about a rise in nationalism and consumer 
fever and says his nation has shifted too far to the right 
the three are by no means typical of most east germans who 
passively endured four decades of sovietimposed rule then quickly 
embraced a fast merger with west germany 
but each to varying degrees took part in what east germany is 
now a sovereign nation with a democratic government 
and each feels in some way opposed to what it will soon 
become a transplanted territory of west germany 
in the beginning i was angry boethig said it was a pity 
a basic democratic movement was overtaken by a unification 
movement the sudden materialism the nationalism 
but i can imagine now why they wanted what they wanted 
the 32yearold berliner taught german literature at east 
berlins prestigious humboldt university and quickly moved into 
circles actively opposed to the old communist government he edited 
an underground literary journal from 198488 working with writers 
barred from official publications 
one day the secret police came to the university and said i 
had to go boethig said after i left i couldnt find a job i 
drove cabs worked in construction i realized i would have to do 
that for a long time 
he applied to leave and like many people considered 
troublemakers was granted a visa in march 1989 six months later 
he got a job teaching german at the university of pittsburgh 
two months after that his former colleagues were leading 
nationwide demonstrations the communist government convulsed and 
collapsed 
in may he came back to work with a west berlin literary society 
the east already had been transormed the university invited 
boethig back to complete his doctoral dissertation 
he plans to accept but finds little in common with east germany 
today the issues his old activist friends are involved with seem 
remote the consumerism of the freed society saddening 
i had mixed feelings after i returned he said what will 
dominate the next years is germany will be busy with itself 
while boethig spoke last week katje havemann was doing what she 
did a decade ago waging war on the government this time the new 
government 
mrs havemann is one of east germanys most lionized activists 
her husband robert a philosophy professor renounced the 
government in the 1970s and became its most famous dissident 
the havemanns spent 2 years under house arrest their home 
surrounded by secret police 
he died in 1982 and she carried on to help form new forum the 
activist group that led the autumn revolt 
mrs havemann was among 22 activists who occupied the 
headquarters of the former secret police sept 4 to keep the files 
from being turned over to west germanys intelligence service 
the group went on a hunger strike sept 12 
many people are concerned now with their social problems 
she said referring to the joblessness that followed the nations 
plunge into capitalism 
but she said she said she fears the united german government 
would become too much like the old communist government if it took 
control of the 6 million secret dossiers of the old administration 
she said she sees no problem with the small crowds that attend 
new forums rallies these days compared with the hundreds of 
thousands last year 
the big difference between now and last fall last fall has 
already happened she said 
new forum never came up with a clear program for a future east 
germany but the christian democrats an approved party by the 
communists reshaped itself after their powerful west german 
namesakes 
the christian democrats espoused conservatism and unencumbered 
capitalism quick unity and western lifestyles they won the free 
elections handily 
carl ordnung 62 joined the party in 1951 and helped reshape it 
last year to fit the new era 
he now works as a foreign policy adviser to prime minister 
lothar de maiziere and will like the government be out of work 
oct 3 
but ordnung a methodist lay preacher said the party and nation 
have swung too far to the right 
he had hoped for a socialist democracy more sympathetic to poor 
people and foreigners less devoted to a marketdriven economy 
i hope east germans after they have consumed western goods 
will see that to consume is not all of human life he said 
ordnungs life has paralleled east germanys he was married 
four days before the nation was created and will celebrate his 41st 
anniversary the day it dissolves 
he was a german army conscript at the end of world war ii and 
went home to recuperate after he was injured in a training 
accident his mother burned his uniform before the soviets came 
he enjoyed travel privileges because of his role in church 
circles but his son then 16 was imprisoned for 2 years in 1973 
for trying to flee 
ordnung believed germanys division was gods penalty for two 
world wars unification he said is a result of public will 
you should respect the will of the people he said but we 
should remember there is another world besides germany 
