<TEXT>
never too much mca records henry johnson 
with his third mca record guitarist henry johnson says he is 
trying to fill the void between strictly commercial music and 
straightahead jazz that is more void than any one musician could 
fill but johnson makes a good attempt 
punched up drums and percussion keyboard overlays and some 
rather bland arrangements give this record its commercial feel 
johnson is able to break free from those constraints often enough 
to keep things interesting listening to the chicagoborn johnson 
it is clear he is capable of making much more interesting 
challenging music 
even so never too much is a cut above the new age elevator 
music so prevalent today on the airwaves and in the record bins 
by james reindl associated press writer 
 
 
 
four impromptus d 935 12 landler d 790 three klaverstucke 
d946 allegretto d 915 by franz schubert london andras 
schiff piano 
the best of schuberts smallscale piano pieces belong to that 
special category of art works which are simple in form yet truly 
complex in experience because of the way they touch us so deeply 
many of domenico scarlattis keyboard sonatas have this quality 
nothing perhaps has it more than schuberts impromptus 
andras schiff has recorded both for london most recently the 
four opus 142 impromptus on this disc 
schiff has all the right instincts in his choice of recording 
repertoire great taste and also adventurousness as shown by 
last years issue of him playing dohnanyi chamber music and 
dvoraks piano concerto performed live 
on the schubert disc his technique is wonderful his approach 
sensitive his interpretations well thoughtout even the disc 
booklet is appealingly simple in its layout and notes 
so mainly in the impromptus one misses all the more that extra 
quality of bringing us into a special realm that focus on the 
depth of simple works 
in the aflat imprompu for instance the middle section is a 
marvel of lyricisim with a lowerupper register dialogue 
accompanied by an excruciatingly beautiful harmonic progression 
but schiff handles the passage without extraordinary poignancy 
nevertheless he manages moments of charm and poetry at other 
times 
the recorded sound is fair schiffs bosendorfer piano has a 
thudding quality at 7426 the cd is generously timed 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
 
 
 
