<TEXT>
paintings splattered from a carbine by niki 
de st phalle or squashed cars hung as art by cesar may not be to 
everyones taste 
but the handsome new museum of contemporary art in the heart of 
the rivieras capital is nevertheless an impressive contribution to 
the city not least because of its monumental modern architecture 
the museum opened amid controversy in june boycotted by several 
local artists and frances culture minister jack lang 
conceived by nices longtime mayor jacques medecin the 
multimilliondollar museum and theater was financed mainly by the 
city with other funds coming from regional and national government 
sources 
the museum had a rough start because of medecins rightwing 
politics coupled with alleged financial fiddling that still have 
the mayor in hot water he was accused of antisemitic remarks last 
spring at a time when desecrations of jewish cemeteries in france 
and elsewhere were causing a storm of protest 
medecin is an avowed admirer of jeanmarie le pen whose 
farright national front espouses antiimmigrant causes that 
attitude is shared by many older conservatives enjoying the high 
life of nice 
perhaps more serious are allegations that medecin has cheated on 
personal taxes as well as in financial deals involving the city he 
is currently under investigation 
in any case the new museum daily is attracting about 1000 
visitors according to spokesmen 
i dont discuss controversy its in the past and im looking 
to the future said head curator pierre chaigneau an art expert 
who has helped open several other important museums and distances 
himself from politics 
he is proud of this museums strictly contemporary role in an 
area that already boasts some excellent museums nices museum of 
fine arts the national chagall museum there the prestigious 
maeght foundation at st paul de vence the leger musem at biot 
this is the only one dedicated exclusively to art from 1950 
onwards said chaigneau who personally favors geometric abstract 
works in the line of josef albers and max bill 
emphasizing neorealism from the 1960s pop art by such artists 
as warhol and lichtenstein as well as minimalist and other trends 
the museums displays include about 2025 percent of works by 
american artists 
the school of nice spearheaded by such artists as yves klein 
armand and martial raysse is wellrepresented the museum is 
especially proud of its large collection of kleins 
threedimensional electric blue figures on various backgrounds by 
the local artist who made international art news before his 
untimely death at age 34 in 1962 
but its the handsome museum complex itself of which nice can be 
most proud 
just behind the old city the gray carrara marblefaced 
structure designed by local architects yves bayard and henri vidal 
includes an octagonal theater and a plaza connecting with four 
monolithic towers housing the art on three levels 
access is easy by way of a redbrick staircase entrance flanked 
by escalators and entry is free of charge a rarity in france 
at the top of the staircase the visitor is dazzled by sun on 
marble and a handsome alexander calder stabile a gift by the 
artist to nice in 1970 
the towers are joined by corridors of glass and steel decorated 
on the interior by vaguely fishshaped metallic ellipses and hung 
with colorful metal stabiles 
in the towers are spacious welllighted exhibition rooms ideal 
for a handsome display of monumentalsized abstracts by such 
artists as morris louis frank stella or jim dine 
with a restaurant tucked into a corner facing the firstlevel 
plaza and theater and a little cafe at the top level the complex 
is equipped to become a gatheringplace for nicois and visitors 
from the top of the museum are fabulous views over old nice to 
the mediterranean a jewish cemetery and the green slopes of the 
cimiez area 
one of the rooftop areas contains a grid of gas jets constructed 
to an yves klein design that sparkles in the evening with jets of 
blue flame a little rooftop garden is planted with typically 
riviera succulents and flowers based on kleins notes for a dream 
garden 
while some nice residents leave quizzical remarks in the 
visitors book about the art the only real complaints so far seem 
to be from animallovers and pigeons apparently some pigeons died 
when stuck to the birdrepellent spread along the rooftop walls 
an unfortunate accident that were striving to correct said 
chaigneau 
