soaring oil prices are pushing ailing airlines 
toward their biggest losses ever and they might become a catalyst 
for a severe shakeup of the troubled industry analysts say 
coupled with the sluggish economy the fallout from the persian 
gulf crisis will hurt all airlines but it might eventually end up 
helping the stronger carriers get bigger at the expense of their 
struggling competitors 
itll make the financially weaker guys get weaker faster 
said kevin murphy an analyst with morgan stanley the strong 
airlines would then grow by default 
under such a scenario analysts say the winners who stand to 
gain market share could be american delta and united losers will 
likely include eastern continental midway pan am and trans 
world the analysts say 
unless something puts the brakes on oil prices and the domestic 
economy finds a quick fix analysts anticipate that the airline 
industry will lose 1 billion to 2 billion for 1990 that would 
surpass 1982s record operating loss of 700 million 
it will be decidedly ugly said samuel buttrick an analyst 
with kidder peabody amp co 
the fundamental problem that the industry faces is excess 
domestic capacity too many seats chasing too few people 
buttrick said he sees the failure of some carriers and the 
removal of their assets from the market as the best way to restore 
equilibrium to the glutted market 
