<TEXT>
the us government has underwritten war risk 
insurance on a commercial ship engaged in normal commercial trade 
for the first time since the korean war in the early 1950s the 
shipping daily lloyds list reported monday 
in a frontpage story lloyds said the 40921ton stonewall 
jackson owned by waterman steamship is the first vessel operating 
commercially to take advantage of the us governments standby war 
risk insurance program since it became effective aug 29 
the lash barge carrier which is about to make a call at the 
jordanian port of aqaba received war risk insurance from the us 
maritime administration on the hull and the 89 barges she carries 
the paper said 
under the program any foreign or us ship may apply to the 
maritime administration for war risk coverage provided the vessel 
is engaged in us trade the maritime agency is permitted to quote 
rates when the rates and conditions being offered in the commercial 
insurance market are considered unfair and unreasonable the paper 
said 
the maritime administration has already issued war risk policies 
for 30 of the merchant vessels taken by the us military sealift 
command for operation desert shield in the gulf lloyds list said 
it has issued its own policies and any claims will be paid by the 
us department of defense 
but the stonewall jackson was the first merchant ship operating 
commercially to take advantage of the program the paper said 
the stonewall jackson was on a voyage from the united states to 
the far east via the suez canal when part of her cargo consigned to 
catholic relief services in india was diverted for the 
international relief effort in jordan it said 
waterman steamship approached the maritime administration for a 
war risks quote for stopping at aqaba which is in a rated war 
risks area it said 
market rates for hull risks to aqaba are currently around 025 
percent lloyds list said 
a us government source quoted by the paper said the maritime 
administration has to quote lower rates for the program to work and 
the commercial insurance market is not very happy with us 
because they see the administration as a potential competitor 
