a high american express co official 
orchestrated a smear campaign of edmond j safra the swiss banker 
who had a fallingout with the financial services giant the wall 
street journal said monday in an investigative report 
harry l freeman then an executive vice president with close 
ties to company chairman james d robinson iii approved the hiring 
of a private detective and a public relations executive who 
investigated safra and then spread rumors about him the journal 
said 
company officials privately blamed the incident on a handful 
of unnamed lowlevel employees the frontpage story said 
but a lengthy investigation by this newspaper reveals evidence 
suggesting the effort to smear mr safra was in fact overseen from 
mr freemans office only steps away from mr robinsons 
false news stories about safra began to surface in early 1988 
linking him to drug dealers money laundering and the mafia the 
journal said 
the newspaper said there was no concrete evidence that robinson 
knew of the campaign against safra although the american express 
chairman had regular contact with one of freemans operatives 
susan cantor 
last year american express publicly apologized to safra 
admitting that people acting on its behalf had tried to discredit 
safra american express paid 8 million to charities of safras 
choice to make amends 
freeman later retired from the company accepting responsibility 
for mistakes made on my watch 
larry armour an american express spokesman said monday that 
the journal story discussed events that took place at least a 
year ago we said at that time what needed to be said in terms of 
the steps we took we admitted that something did indeed go awry 
we apologized about it 
armour continued we ran a very extensive internal 
investigation that was run by the audit committee of the board of 
directors they came back with recommendations on policy and 
procedures which we have put in place 
its senseless to respond to old news no matter how 
colorfully someone chooses to repackage it armour said 
the journal said it gathered its information from interviews 
with dozens of people involved in the safra affair including 
journalists private detectives and 15 current and former american 
express executives the story headlined the vendetta was 
written by reporter bryan burrough 
the journal said american express and safra began to fall out 
