<TEXT>
chase manhattan corps announcement that it 
will slash its dividend and eliminate 5000 jobs could signal 
impending cutbacks by other major banks analysts said monday 
the nations secondlargest bank said friday it would halve its 
dividend this quarter because it planned to set aside more than 
650 million by sept 30 to bolster reserves for loans that may go 
bad most of the loans financed commercial real estate 
but analysts said real estate is just one trouble spot for major 
banks as the economy deteriorates 
among other concerns are the loans that helped finance the wave 
of corporate buyouts in the 1980s as business slows at the 
companies acquired through these leveraged buyouts the likelihood 
that the loans will be repaid in full diminishes analysts say 
one industry source who spoke on condition of anonymity said 
chase may be just the first among top banks to scale back the 
source said citibank the nations largest and chemical banking 
corp no 6 both could be forced to retrench due to low levels of 
reserves compared with potentially troubled loans 
other major banks are going to watch closely to see whether 
the dividend cut hurts chases standing among the financial 
community before considering following suit said analyst mark 
lynch of bear stearns amp co 
one major bank manufacturers hanover corp issued a statement 
that it has every reason to believe its dividend will remain 
unchanged 
and its not just the huge money center banks that are 
hurting some regional banks particularly in new england the 
southeast and the midwest have been troubled for months as the 
strong real estate market of the 1980s went bust 
two smaller banks said friday they would cut their dividends as 
they prepare for tougher times midlantic corp of edison nj 
slashed its dividend in half as it announced it expects to lose at 
least 150 million this quarter southeast banking corp of miami 
said it would eliminate its dividend entirely this quarter due to a 
loss it projects will be 87 million 
a stable history of dividend payments is one of the key reasons 
investors put their money in bank stocks chase became the first 
major new york bank to cut its dividend in at least 15 years lynch 
said 
not surprisingly wall street reacted severely to the news of 
the bank dividend cuts chases stock lost 1 a share friday and an 
additional 162 monday to close at 1112 earlier this year 
it was as high as 3075 
among other bank stocks monday citicorp fell 50 cents to close 
at 1525 chemical bank lost 187 to end at 1512 and 
manufacturers hanover slipped 25 cents to 2275 
the decline in bank stocks was blamed in part for a drop in the 
entire market friday and monday 
the bond market also has shown concern prices of notes to raise 
cash issued by citicorp chemical bank and manufacturers hanover 
all dropped monday 
there is a lot of hysteria and uncertainty as to what the 
future holds for banking its scaring the heck out of everyone 
said stephen berman who follows banking for the investment firm 
county natwest usa 
berman said the concern stems in part from the fact that banks 
are a microcosm of the economy as the economy deteriorates some 
investors fear banks will go down with it 
the fear about the health of banks also arises from the fact 
that little is publicly disclosed about what banks hold in their 
loan portfolios 
the banks are a blind pool of assets lynch said people 
are assuming that the worst of everything is in the loan 
portfolios 
at the same time regulators are stepping up pressure on banks 
to have adequate provisions to cover bad loans especially in light 
of the savings and loan debacle 
but analysts said some of the concern about the health of banks 
is misplaced many banks already have put aside enough money to 
cover potentially bad loans and they shouldnt need to scale back 
unless the nation enters a long recession 
however a number of analysts said citicorp may be in a riskier 
position than is generally believed 
the party line at citicorp is that theyre more conservative 
than other banks the level of problem loans doesnt hold the same 
degree of loss potential i have some difficulty with that 
berman said 
he said that as of june 30 citicorp had put aside enough money 
to cover 25 percent of the loans it identified as potentially 
troubled by contrast by the end of this quarter chase will have 
50 percent of its potentially bad loans covered by reserves he 
said 
