honda motor co ltd will equip all of 
its cars with driver and passengerside air bags by the 1994 model 
year the companys top executive said monday 
nobuhiko kawamoto who became the japanese companys president 
and chief executive officer last june told reporters the devices 
will replace automatic seat belts now on its cars 
kawamoto in his first us tour as head of honda declined to 
speculate how many honda and acura cars the company would sell in 
the united states by the time air bags became standard equipment 
through the first eight months of this year honda sold 593508 
cars up 112 percent from the same time last year 
currently chrysler corp equips all of its usmade cars with 
driverside air bags but cars it receives from other companies 
notably mitsubishi motors corp do not have the safety devices 
general motors corp said it will expand the use of driver and 
passenger side air bags to all of its domestically designed cars by 
late 1995 for the 1996 model year ford motor co said by the 
mid1990s it would equip all of its cars with driver and passenger 
side air bags 
on others matters kawamoto said monday 
honda plans no further plant expansions in the united states in 
the near future he said the company will focus on its us 
research and development operations and increase the amount of 
usmade components in its cars assembled in hondas two ohio 
plants past the current level of about 75 percent 
the expansion of production capacity is the second 
priority he said hondas marysville ohio plant is running 
near to its capacity while its new east liberty ohio factory is 
slowly increasing its production toward capacity 
no decision has been made on whether honda will build a minivan 
for the us or asian markets 
we still have many things to do like the accord wagon 
kawamoto said honda will introduce a station wagon version of its 
popular accord sedan this fall for the 1991 model year 
like other automakers honda opposes legislation in congress 
now mandating a 20percent increase in auto manufacturers 
corporate average fuel economy ratings by the turn of the century 
