the senate narrowly rejected a proposal monday 
night to aid autoworkers laid off in any required shift by 
automakers to highermileage cars 
in debate on a bill to require cars to average 40 miles per 
gallon the senate voted 4946 to reject an amendment by sen paul 
simon dill that would have provided special unemployment 
assistance for those workers 
a vote on whether to close off debate on the bill was scheduled 
for tuesday 
the passage of this amendment will doom this bill declared 
sen slade gorton rwash a cosponsor 
later the senate agreed 5540 to a include in the legislation 
new incentives for automakers to produce vehicles that can run on 
alternative fuels such as methanol ethanol or natural gas the 
measure would allow manufacturers to claim credits against fuel 
efficiency requirements if they produce such vehicles 
similar fuel economy legislation has been introduced in the 
house but has yet to emerge from committee 
in earlier debate on the legislation opponents argued that the 
higher fuel economy requirements would be a death blow to the 
midsize family sedan and force automakers to produce only small 
cars 
sen richard bryan dnev chief sponsor of the legislation 
disputed such claims arguing higher fuel efficiency can be 
achieved without sacrificing the sixpassenger automobile 
it means smaller cars it means less safe cars declared 
sen donald riegle dmich who has led efforts to block 
consideration of the measure 
the legislations supporters maintained that manufacturers have 
shown in the past that they can come up with technologies to 
improve fuel efficiency greatly and still provide customers with a 
broad range of vehicle models 
in aiming to reduce the nations dependence on foreign oil the 
bill would would require cars to achieve on a fleet average 35 mpg 
by 1995 and 40 mpg by 2001 he said that would eventually save 28 
million barrels of oil daily 
the automakers have said they cant meet those goals without 
making cars dramatically smaller and stopping production of midsize 
and large vehicles 
bryan read statements by auto industry executives in the early 
1970s predicting the demise of the family sedan as a result of fuel 
efficiency requirements then under consideration 
that just didnt happen the sixpassenger vehicle is here 
just as it was before said bryan 
</TEXT>
