<TEXT>
lockheed corp rejected texas financier 
harold simmons latest advances on monday saying his attempt to 
buy another 10 million shares of the companys stock was a ploy to 
take control on the cheap 
simmons who controls 198 percent of lockheeds stock lost a 
proxy battle in march for control of the calabasas califbased 
company the nations sixth largest military contractor 
he had asked lockheed to void its poison pill takeover 
defense under that provision if anyone buys more than 20 percent 
of lockheeds stock the company can sell new stock to other 
shareholders at a discount that would dilute simmons holdings 
making a takeover prohibitively expensive 
lockheeds board rejected simmons request to revoke the 
provision so his nl industries inc can buy 10 million shares at 
35 per share from lockheeds employee stock ownership plan or up 
to 350 million worth of stock in the open market that would give 
him control of 35 percent of the stock 
the directors did agree to suspend the poison pill if an offer 
meets certain conditions notably that it must be for 100 percent 
of the company be in cash and be approved by a majority of 
shareholders not counting the one making the offer 
reached by telephone in texas simmons declined to talk about 
lockheeds decision id really rather not comment until ive had 
a chance to study the whole thing he said 
like all defense contractors lockheed faces potentially tough 
times from spending cuts by the us government its stock closed 
up a fraction monday at 2575 far below the average 43 per share 
that simmons paid for his stake 
lockheed chairman daniel m tellep said its directors had met 
with simmons several times since march to brief him about the 
company 
simmons lockheed stock is now worth about 200 million less 
than he paid for it he maintains however that he is a longterm 
investor with no intention of selling even if the stock price rose 
sharply 
